Epoch:0 | TOPIC | Scientist0:This is a compelling direction to explore, especially given the growing demand for trustworthy and reproducible AI systems. Building on the team’s strengths in interpretability and model robustness, I believe this question taps into a critical yet underexamined aspect of neural text classifiers: *attribution stability across functionally equivalent models*.

Even when two models achieve nearly identical performance—same architecture, training data, hyperparameters, but different random weight initializations—they can learn distinct internal representations due to the non-convex nature of training dynamics. Now, if we apply feature-based interpretability methods (e.g., LIME, SHAP, Integrated Gradients), do they yield consistent explanations? Or do small differences in learned weights lead to drastically different feature attributions, even when predictions are functionally equivalent?

This isn’t just about explanation variance—it's about whether we can trust explanations as faithful reflections of model behavior. If two models perform the same but are explained differently, it undermines the reliability of these tools in high-stakes domains like healthcare or legal NLP.

We could design controlled experiments using standard text classification benchmarks (e.g., SST-2, AG News), train multiple instances of the same architecture with different seeds, verify functional equivalence via test accuracy and prediction consistency, then apply several feature-attribution methods. The key metric would be attribution similarity—measured via rank correlation, cosine similarity of attribution vectors, or Jaccard overlap of top-k important features.

An innovative extension would be probing whether certain architectures (e.g., Transformers vs. CNNs) or regularization techniques (e.g., dropout, data augmentation) promote more stable attributions. Even more impactful: can we develop a new interpretability method—or a post-hoc calibration technique—that produces invariant explanations across stochastic training runs?

This work sits at the intersection of interpretability, reproducibility, and model diagnostics, and could set a new standard for how we evaluate not just model performance, but explanation quality.
========================================
