Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: My motivation stems from a critical gap in current interpretability research: while feature-based methods are widely used to explain neural text classifiers, their stability and reliability remain questionable—especially when models are functionally equivalent but initialized differently. Paper 1 highlights the alarming lack of robustness in interpretations across random initializations, suggesting that attributions may reflect artifacts of training dynamics rather than meaningful input-feature relationships. However, existing work stops at diagnosing instability without leveraging it as a diagnostic tool itself. I propose flipping the perspective: instead of treating instability as a flaw to be minimized, we can treat it as a *probe* into the trustworthiness of interpretability methods. The core intuition is that if an attribution method produces wildly different explanations for models with identical performance and decision boundaries (but different initializations), then either the method is unstable or the features it identifies are not truly central to the model’s function. By systematically measuring this variance and correlating it with functional equivalence, we can evaluate not just model interpretations, but the *interpretability methods themselves*. This idea integrates insights from Paper 1 (randomization tests) and Paper 2 (multi-axis explanation via necessity/sufficiency), but diverges by focusing on methodological evaluation rather than explanation generation. It also avoids the computational burden highlighted in Paper 3 by staying within feature-attribution space. Crucially, this approach offers a new meta-evaluation framework—one that assesses how well interpretability methods capture stable, functional semantics rather than spurious correlations.

