{
  "Idea": "This paper proposes a novel meta-evaluation framework for feature-based interpretability methods in neural text classification, centered on the concept of 'attribution stability under functional equivalence.' Specifically, we investigate whether state-of-the-art attribution techniques (e.g., Integrated Gradients, LIME, SHAP, attention rollout) produce consistent feature importance rankings across multiple instances of functionally equivalent neural text classifiers—models that achieve near-identical performance on benchmark datasets (e.g., SST-2, Hate Speech Detection) but differ only in random initialization and resulting parameter spaces. While these models are behaviorally indistinguishable in terms of accuracy, F1, and calibration, prior work suggests their internal representations may vary significantly. We hypothesize that reliable interpretability methods should yield similar attributions across such models, as they solve the same task using statistically equivalent strategies. Deviations in attribution patterns would indicate either methodological instability or reliance on non-essential features. To test this, we introduce two diagnostic metrics: (1) Attribution Consistency Score (ACS), which measures pairwise similarity (via rank correlation or cosine similarity) of feature importance vectors across models; and (2) Functional Divergence Index (FDI), which quantifies the degree to which attribution differences correlate with subtle shifts in decision boundary geometry, measured through probing classifiers and counterfactual perturbation analysis. Furthermore, we extend the analysis by decomposing attributions into necessity and sufficiency components (inspired by Paper 2), allowing us to assess whether instability arises more from what features are *required* versus what features are *sufficient* for prediction. This dual-axis view enables deeper insight into whether unstable attributions stem from sensitivity to redundant features (high sufficiency variance) or inconsistent identification of core evidence (high necessity variance). The ultimate goal is to establish a benchmark for evaluating the robustness of interpretability methods—not just against noise, but against benign variations in model realization. This has profound implications for NLP practitioners who rely on explanations for debugging, fairness auditing, and regulatory compliance. A method that fails this stability test cannot be trusted to reveal true model reasoning, regardless of its fidelity or intuitiveness.",
