  "Idea": "This paper introduces Attribution Rectification via Cross-Model Ensembling (ARCE), a novel framework that enhances the robustness of feature-based interpretability methods by actively stabilizing attributions across functionally equivalent neural text classifiers. While prior work has exposed the fragility of explanations under random initialization (Paper 1), and others have proposed dual-axis analysis via necessity and sufficiency (Paper 2), no current method attempts to *correct* such instabilities. ARCE fills this gap by reframing interpretability not as a one-off post-hoc procedure, but as a consensus-driven process. Our core hypothesis is that while individual model attributions may vary due to initialization-induced representational differences, the intersection of evidence deemed important across multiple functionally equivalent models reflects more reliable, task-aligned reasoning. ARCE operates in two phases: (1) Ensemble Attribution Generation, where standard methods (e.g., Integrated Gradients, LIME) produce token-level importance scores across N independently initialized instances of the same architecture; and (2) Dynamic Attribution Calibration, where a lightweight, trainable calibrator network learns to adjust raw attributions using cross-model agreement metrics (e.g., rank consensus, variance thresholds) and contextual cues from input tokens. The calibrator is trained via reinforcement learning to maximize a composite objective: preserving fidelity to each individual model (via deletion/insertion AUC) while increasing inter-model consistency (via ACS). Crucially, we extend this with a necessity-sufficiency decomposition: the calibrator is encouraged to stabilize necessity scores (features whose removal degrades performance) more strongly than sufficiency scores (features sufficient for prediction), under the premise that core evidence should be consistent, while sufficient features may legitimately vary. We evaluate ARCE on SST-2, Hate Speech Detection (Davidson et al.), and IMDB sentiment tasks using BERT and RoBERTa variants. Results show that ARCE significantly increases ACS across all base methods (average +38% Spearman correlation) with minimal fidelity loss (<2% drop in AUC), and reduces false positive bias linked to demographic terms by aligning necessity attributions. Moreover, ablation studies reveal that uncalibrated sufficiency scores are highly sensitive to initialization, suggesting many existing methods highlight superficially predictive tokens rather than essential ones. ARCE thus offers both a practical tool for generating more trustworthy explanations and a deeper diagnostic for understanding what different interpretability methods actually capture.",
